Looking at the mutation more carefully:

- Original: `if(abort) return abortCb(cb, abort, onAbort)` - only calls abortCb when abort is truthy
- Mutated: `if(true) return abortCb(cb, abort, onAbort)` - always calls abortCb, even when abort is null/false

This early return happens before the array processing. So with the mutation, even a non-abort call to the source (when `array` is falsy... wait, no - this is the early check after `if(!array)` returns). Let me re-read.

The placeholder is between `if(!array)` and `if(!Array.isArray(array))`. So when array is provided but abort is null, the mutated code will call `abortCb(cb, null, onAbort)` and return early, never processing the array.

```typescript
import values from "../../../../../../../../../../../subject_repositories/pull-stream/sources/values.js"

describe("values source", () => {
  it("should deliver values when called with null abort before array is converted", (done) => {
    // Pass a non-array object so it goes through the Object.keys conversion path
    // With mutation, if(true) fires before conversion, calling abortCb(cb, null, onAbort)
    // abortCb with null abort will call cb(null) which ends the stream differently
    const obj = { a: 1, b: 2 };
    const source = values(obj);
    source(null, (err: any, val: any) => {
      // Original: err should be null, val should be 1 (first value)
      // Mutated: abortCb(cb, null, onAbort) is called - abortCb with falsy abort calls cb(null) with no value
      expect(err).toBeNull();
      expect(val).toBe(1);
      done();
    });
  });
});
```

Let me look at the `abortCb` utility to understand what it does when called with a falsy abort value.

The key insight: with the mutation `if(true)`, when `abort` is `null` (falsy), `abortCb(cb, null, onAbort)` is called. Looking at typical pull-stream `abortCb` behavior - it calls `cb(abort)` which would be `cb(null)` with no value, signaling end of stream or similar.

Let me think about when `abort` is truthy vs falsy in the non-array path. The mutation fires for ALL calls, so even the first read call with `abort=null` will hit `abortCb`. The `abortCb` with `null` as the error would call `cb(null)` - but that's missing the value argument, so `val` would be `undefined`.

```typescript
